Round count is <350 total. This is the most accurate handgun I've ever owned, or shot. This unit is in great shape, with only a few small spots where the STI finish is wearing off (they are known for a light finish), along with a faint idiot scratch from the FFL that I picked up the pistol from new. 

Work performed by CCP:
Remove thin grips and bushings
Install standard grip bushings in frame
Install a nice set of Cocobolo wood grips
Remove stock STI trigger and install a flat trigger
Install new checkered MSH
bevel and reblue the thumb safety
preform a 3.5LB trigger job (trigger is amazing)
perform a disco cut

All in all, I have $1800+ in this pistol, I'll take $1500 cash, or I'll trade for a Colt 1911. Depending on the Colt model, I might need some cash to boot. Looking for a 70 series gun here, prefer older models (no older than WWII though), or one of the new repro WW1/WW2 models.

I purchased it from the original owner for $2,000 and since then I have had it to my gunsmith who did some trigger work on it, and I added the Crimson Trace grips.

The only problem I had (and the reason for the trip to the gunsmith) was trying to insert a magazine. The problem turned out to be with the trigger stirrup, which needed to be worked on and fitted properly.  Since then, everything is as it should be.
